Athletes are often written about in biographies because they are so interesting to read about, what they have all done and how they have all fought and competed, but rarely do we see biographies written about coaches.
Indeed, a book like "Klopp in Full Steam" must be special for this man to actually have a biography written about him while he is currently at the top of his game.
Yes, I must say it is a superb book, and when I started reading it, I was pleasantly surprised to see that my good acquaintance Aet Süvari had actually translated it into Estonian. We have been in several football studios together, but she never mentioned that she was translating this Klopp book at the same time, so it was a nice surprise to begin with.
So, you know this man personally. When did you first meet?
Well, let's go back almost twenty-four years ago, it was in 1996 when I first saw him and went to play in the German second division from Estonia. And, well, let's say at that moment when I joined the team, Jürgen Klopp was actually injured, he had a very serious injury in football terms, a torn cruciate ligament, and it is even mentioned in the book that he came back from this cruciate ligament injury in three months.
Completely unique, as it usually takes six to nine months, and I can confirm that this man was ready for training three months after that injury, and I think he played his first game around three and a half months later.
How good of a football player was he?
Well, actually, it is very well written in the book how people used to joke about his first touch being so long that the opponent always caught up to him, meaning he wasn't considered a very technical player, but what he had in absolute top class was his leadership.
He is 193 centimeters tall, even a bit taller than me, but that was his absolutely extreme skill, and his will to win, that was something extraordinary, and I saw it firsthand on the football field, and we all see it today, next to the football field, as a coach.
But did the thought ever cross your mind, when he was still chasing the ball on the field, that at some point I will actually end my career as an athlete, what's next? Well, going into coaching is a quite logical choice, and this man, Klopp, really gets teams working so hard that they start winning.
Yes, it's absolutely not surprising that he became a coach, as he was always such a spiritual leader of the team. For example, I remember very well the Christmas party in 1996, where we had a great first half, finished second, and Jürgen Klopp spoke there. There were also some smaller competitions, and he didn't really want to lose there either. Definitely, he had the material and he was one hundred percent the coach's confidant, so it was evident in the materials.

Well, what we shouted out here, to make it clear why Jürgen Klopp and Ragnar Klavan are in one picture, well, here they are in one picture, embracing each other. Klopp took Klavan to play.

Indeed, of course, Klopp might be the one who could talk about the coach the most today, but this picture clearly characterizes what is also a recurring theme in the book, that he is incredibly empathetic, he can make all the players play because he is, well, of course he is not friends with everyone, but he creates an atmosphere where all the players love him, even when he has left the club, there are good words to say about Klopp, because he is honest, he doesn't do anything behind their backs, when it's time to part ways, he tells the player.

But at the same time, when we look at those competitions and what he does there on the sidelines, he doesn't always seem friendly, rather like a fiery man. It's also noticeable that when we see this picture, I have actually seen how he went to attack corner kicks with a similar expression, with his teeth clenched, even back then, and, well, we all start running after that ball because we had the same determination at that time, and, well, it's a bit of a crazy look, isn't it, but exactly, exactly the next moment he is a warm person with a wide smile, he admits himself that sometimes his emotions get the better of him, for example, at the club.

It's like the opposite situation now, right.
The former sports director of the football club, Kristjan Haidel, who also took me into the club at that time, when he gave Klopp the opportunity to work as a coach, vividly described how they won their first game. When a goal was scored, he said that he himself didn't even know where Klopp was. Klopp ran somewhere, not even knowing where, and when he looked for him, he was already basically on the stands, a very emotional person.

Which type of players does he prefer, thinking men or obedient men?

Since I read the book, I know that he has never reached the absolute top of the world, except for Liverpool. For example, neither in Malta nor in Tartu. He raised young players and that is a good chapter about how players were chosen in Malta when they were already in the top league.

When some self-proclaimed star players came there and thought, "Wait, now we will start playing and push others to play," the first thing Klopp actually wants to know is whether the player is willing to run and whether the player is willing to work. Because Klopp's tactics, how the team plays, is very intense. They constantly try to press the opponent high and win the ball immediately and attack immediately. They don't play like losing the ball calmly and waiting to see what the opponent does.

Let's say that in the early 2000s, he started doing this and it was actually innovative in Germany. So, those lazy players couldn't go to Klopp's team.

His contract with Liverpool is still valid until 2023 or something like that. What are the sweetest moments for this coach? He has collected many of them, the Champions League, right? What else could come?

Yes, interestingly, he was in Mainz for seven years, in Dortmund for seven years, and in 2015 he went to Liverpool. Let's say that the first few years, two or three years, it takes time for him to achieve the result. Now Liverpool is the champion, he is close to the champagne as a winner. Now it's like he has two more years to move forward, if we go into numbers a bit.
But well, the question is, where to go from there, well, I think he is the kind of man who could someday lead the German code.
