And we now have Kadri Kõusaar visiting us, who recently returned from Jordan, where she is making her fourth feature film, why Jordan?
Because there is a beautiful desert there. And I have been dreaming of making this desert film for over ten years.
What kind of film is it then, does it carry the title "Dead Woman"? It is very difficult to make a film about a dead woman if she is dead all the time, then, then there is not much action to show.
Well, it's more of a metaphor, this title, that maybe she is emotionally dead, for example, and then something happens to her in the desert that brings her back to life, we can interpret the title in a different way.
But yes, it is about a Swedish female journalist who goes to fulfill a work assignment in Egypt and unfortunately she is kidnapped or abducted instead.
But from this abduction, an incredible sincere love story develops.
Well, if we talk about Jordan now, how does life there work in terms of Covid and in general? You were now, we sent you an invitation earlier, but you were in quarantine here in Estonia because everyone coming from abroad had to quarantine, now it's over for you, how does life in Jordan work in terms of Covid and in general?
Well, it's a Middle Eastern country, so there are certain peculiarities in terms of politics and such, there are many sensitive areas, but generally they have managed quite well in the Covid crisis, so in the spring, a military regime was imposed because people simply did not listen at first, to stay together, no, we couldn't go anywhere because the whole world locked down before that.
But then there was a military curfew and you were only allowed to go to the grocery store or pharmacy, and if you violated the rules, you were put in prison, so it was quite strict there, well, since people don't have money, they had to be put in prison.
But then, in general, they were listened to and thanks to that, these measures were implemented and were quite strict. Currently, there is still a requirement to wear masks in public places, and we also had specific instructions from the Royal Film Corporation on how to conduct the shoots, including testing every four to five days. The technical crew had to wear masks, except for the actors. Of course, in indoor settings, it was not always technically possible, especially in thirty-degree desert heat. However, outdoors, among the expedition team, the infection rate was very low because they were always in open air. It seems that the virus does not spread in the same way as in the city.

Did the entire film crew manage to stay healthy?

Yes, fortunately. I was just thinking about what would have happened if something had happened to one of the key people, like myself, the cinematographer, or the lead actors. It would have caused a major setback.

Well, both in Sweden and Estonia, the Covid situation is probably much worse than in Jordan.

Yes, that's true. But I tried to explain this to an official there, that we need to follow these guidelines. Luckily, everything went smoothly. We had a couple of cases among the local crew who had worked elsewhere before, but fortunately, we were able to replace them with other people.

How did everything else go? How is the general life and organization there when you need film equipment, assistants, and so on?

Well, we had a very good local co-production company or a company responsible for the production. And by the way, Jordan is a major film country. We shared shooting locations with Hollywood giants like Star Wars and The Martian. And wasn't that famous movie also filmed there? The locals have a lot of experience, and compared to them, we are just small players. They are very professional, and you just have to book and negotiate the price with the production team in advance.

Speaking of prices, how expensive is Jordan as a country?
Well, yes, I suppose so, the food and gasoline are cheaper than in Estonia, but otherwise it's actually more or less the same, well, you know, it's not really a third world country, and right next to it is Israel, which is quite expensive, and now of course, thanks to the coronavirus, everything is more expensive in that sense, for example, there are specific rules for catering, and everything has to be packaged separately, and I'm just thinking with horror about the pile of plastic that creates.
It's inevitable, because the rules state that everyone must have their own container, and all things must be packaged in separate containers, so you can't put them all in one pot.
What kind of food was offered there, what do they eat there at all?
They eat a lot of fresh vegetables, salads, grilled vegetables, and of course hummus and the food is delicious, a bit spicy, and grilled meat, in that sense, regarding the food.
You do look like you could be a vegan, but you're not.
No, no, I'm not, I've never tried it and I stopped at the doctor's, so.
Do you prefer to eat meat or?
No, well, everyone is different, well, at least I've honestly tried.
How does Islam affect it, Jordan is an Islamic country, does that religion somehow play a role there, did it affect your work on the film?
Well, in that sense, it did affect it, because it's actually a theme in my film, it's about the relationship between two people from completely different cultural backgrounds, and we also had crew members who were very religious and prayed five times a day and so on, and they also advised me when I had to advise the actor, who is Palestinian but not actively religious.
So in that sense, but they are very liberal and progressive, there is religious freedom, it's not Saudi Arabia, which is right next door, it's peaceful, believe what you want or how you want.
I understand that it's an Estonian film, you are the director, the screenwriter is Estonian, and the production team, but the film is not in Estonian at all, and the lead actor is Swedish, and the shooting took place in Jordan, is it somehow more complicated, can one thing be even more complicated?
Actually, it's not complicated, it's always easy when you have a specific idea and vision, then everything is very simple, I wanted to portray the relationship between a Western female journalist and a Palestinian man, and I wanted it to happen in the desert, which has its own poetry and symbolism in the film.
And then it just happened that I, although the action takes place here, it is currently too dangerous there, as there is an ISIS nest in Northern China at the moment and no one would give you any kind of insurance or guarantees, but Jordan is a friendly film country, so it happened that unfortunately, since the lead actress, well, she is a photojournalist or, well, so to speak, a foreign correspondent in Estonian, as we know, such a profession does not exist in Estonian journalism.

Desert, you have brought up the desert several times in our conversation, did the desert meet your expectations?

Yes, yes, indeed, it is beautiful and it has an impact and it even "infected" those crew members who had not previously been in that area, it really is stunning and all that silence and, and that kind of eternity.

Indeed, I think it touched our soul and heart.

When can we go to the cinema to see the dead woman?

Well, I hope in the year 2021, because here we simply need to finish the last bit, which should take place in Estonia and Sweden, so we currently have, let's say, ninety percent in the can, but since some funding sources have collapsed or dried up due to the corona crisis, we hope that in the new year our own Film Institute and Ministry of Culture will show some mercy.

So, there is a lack of money, I understand, more than half of the film is completed, but...

Not even half, but ninety percent, but we just need a little more, for example, for such non-essential elements that may be important to some of the main Estonian people, such as my salary as a screenwriter, director, and producer, and the salary of the cinematographer, Sten-Lille, for example.

Well, unfortunately, you can't feed the nightingale with a song, so in that sense, you have to think about these things a little.

Thank you for coming, Kadri Kõusar, and we hope that the financial matters will be sorted out and the money for your film will be found so that it can reach the cinemas. Thank you for coming.

Thank you.

